Praga -- tA Detour to Moscow: Vladimir Makanin’s Underground, or the Snare of the Subterranean -- t“Cherboslovats, Romongolians, Sweeks”: Yuri Andrukhovych’s Moscow as a “Junkspace” of Cultures -- tPlanar Cities and Their Urban Devastation: Andrzej Stasiuk’s Post-Socialist Warsaw -- tAggressive Localism: Stasiuk and Andrukhovych as Secretaries of the Provincial -- tBackstory “Metropolis, Mass, Meat Factory”: Tot Art and the Orange Alternative as Chefs of the “Semantic Porridge” -- t“It All Started in Gdańsk!”: Berlin’s Club of Polish Losers -- tConclusion or, Entropy of the Underground -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Illustrations -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe literary scholar Alfrun Kliems explores the aesthetic strategies of Eastern European underground literature, art, film and music in the decades before and after the fall of communism, ranging from the ‘father’ of Prague Underground, Egon Bondy, to the neo-Dada Club of Polish Losers in Berlin. The works she considers are "underground" in the sense that they were produced illegally, or were received as subversive after the regimes had fallen. Her study challenges common notions of ‘Underground’ as an umbrella term for nonconformism. Rather, it depicts it as a sociopoetic reflection of modernity, intimately linked to urban settings, with tropes and aesthetic procedures related to Surrealism, Dadaism, Expressionism, and, above all, pop and counterculture. The author discusses these commonalities and distinctions in Czech, Polish, Slovak, Ukrainian, Russian, and German authors, musicians, and filmmakers. She identifies intertextual relations across languages and generations, and situates her findings in a transatlantic context (including the Beat Generation, Susan Sontag, Neil Young) and the historical framework of Romanticism and modernity (including Baudelaire and Brecht). Despite this wide brief, the book never loses sight of its core message: Underground is no arbitrary expression of discontent, but rather the result of a fundamental conflict at the socio-philosophical roots of modernity.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCities and towns in literature. 0aCounterculturezEurope, EasternxHistoryy20th century. 0aCounterculture--Europe, Eastern--History--20th century. 0aLiterature, ExperimentalzEurope, EasternxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Experimental--Europe, Eastern--History and criticism. 0aPerforming arts and literaturezEurope, EasternxHistoryy20th century. 0aPerforming arts and literaturezEurope, EasternxHistoryy21st century. 0aUnderground literaturezEurope, EasternxHistory and criticism. 0aUnderground literature--Europe, Eastern--History and criticism. 0aUrbanization in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh  aCommunism, Fiction, Late 20th century, Literature, Modernity, Post-communism, Urban studies.1 aSchneider, Jake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2021z978311078049940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633863985423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633863985/original  a978-3-11-078049-9  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles